description:
Meet the dynamic duo behind the popular Woodlands Sourdough. Ms Nurhasanah Johar is in charge of making sourdough loaves while her husband, Mr Chalith Kariyawasam, handles other bakes such as brownies.

The couple first met 15 years ago while doing a part-time degree in the same school. They used to do sports together until their love of baking bread took over in 2013.

After taking part in pop-up markets and offering a bread subscription service, the self-taught bakers opened @woodlandssd in 2016.

The pair hits a decade of marriage this year. "Sure, we may fight since we are together 24/7É?? But we learn to discuss what we did wrong when we are not so emotional,É?ù says Ms Nurhasanah. É??I don't think I can find a better assistant than my husband."

Follow @straitstimesfood for more on SingaporeÉ??s food scene.

description:
The air travel bubble, which would have allowed for leisure travel between the 2 sides, had been suspended indefinitely since November last year, after a spike in Covid-19 cases in Hong Kong.

Both cities had earlier agreed that the arrangement would be suspended if the 7-day average of unlinked coronavirus cases in either city exceeded 5. Hong Kong's figure currently stands at 4.57.

description:
During the Covid-19 circuit breaker last year, migrant workers were not allowed to leave their dormitories, not even to get food.

After learning about their predicament, Mrs Cherie Tseng and her husband Tseng Wun Hsiung rang up friends and relatives for donations, looked for catering firms, as well as Grab drivers to deliver food.

In 2 weeks, they raised more than $100,000 to provide over 10,000 meals to about 670 workers. The funds also went towards topping up SIM cards for 1,500 workers.

Full story in bio @straits_times

Some of the best of these will be on show this weekend at Through The Lens, a photography exhibition by The Straits Times and World Press Photo (WPP), which will run until Feb 7.

The exhibition at the National Museum of Singapore will feature ST photojournalists' coverage of the Covid-19 pandemic in Singapore, as well as photos submitted for the 2020 WPP competition.

Find out more about the exhibition, link in bio @straits_times

description:
Mr Das Dipto, who moved from Bangladesh to work in Singapore 8 years ago, was cleaning a boom lift he used for pruning trees, when a frantic woman approached him and his colleague for help.

She pointed to a boy, who was clinging on to laundry poles while on a third-floor ledge. The child had climbed out of a kitchen window after waking up to discover that he was home alone.

He decided the best way to reach him was to use the boom lift. With his colleague steering the machine, Mr Dipto reached out with both arms and lifted the boy into the platform.

Recalling the incident, Mr Dipto said he was so engrossed in saving the boy that he did not notice that a small crowd had gathered.

Link in bio @straits_times
üì∏: Ng Sor Luan, KuÃÇaÃÇsÃåhaÃÇ DÃåaÃÇsÃå/Facebook
#everydayheroes #StraitsTimes

The 83-year-old cruise passenger tested positive for Covid-19 on Wednesday morning while on board the ship. However, 2 tests that were conducted on Wednesday night were found to be negative.
The National Public Health Laboratory conducted another test on Thursday to confirm his Covid-19 status, which MOH said was also negative.
MOH said it has rescinded the quarantine orders of close contacts who were earlier quarantined as a precaution while investigations were being done.
The ministry added that it will support the laboratory on board the Quantum of the Seas ship in its review of its testing processes.

description:
Update: Singapore and Hong Kong have decided to defer the start of the air travel bubble to beyond this month given that the number of local unlinked cases in Hong Kong is still high, says CAAS.
The exact start date of the arrangement will be reviewed late this month.
The move comes as Hong Kong hunkers down under harsher social distancing measures in anticipation of what health authorities have warned could be the worst Covid-19 wave so far.
Hong Kong's daily new infections have crossed 70 for more than a week.
The spike was led initially by a growing dance club cluster of more than 500, most of whom are tai tais and their young dancing instructors.
Link in bio @straits_times
#travelbubble #hongkong #singapore #coronavirus #covid19 #StraitsTimes

comments: As 1 country it is easy to say what needs to get done and everyone toe the line. This takes some leadership foresight and a public who's generally willing to cooperate. Opening up a country to another? Unless both countries have the common same detection, tracing, control methods and direction (just like 1 country) setting measurements to determine when to pull the plug is not enough. Are the countries in a travel bubble willing to adapt and adjust to each other for a common way forward- just like a single country's response, containment and treatment methods? Are the people of both countries trusting enough of the other? If not, then travel bubbles anywhere would be some way off.

Update: Singapore and Hong Kong have decided to defer the start of the air travel bubble to beyond this month given that the number of local unlinked cases in Hong Kong is still high, says CAAS.
The exact start date of the arrangement will be reviewed late this month.
The move comes as Hong Kong hunkers down under harsher social distancing measures in anticipation of what health authorities have warned could be the worst Covid-19 wave so far.
Hong Kong's daily new infections have crossed 70 for more than a week.
The spike was led initially by a growing dance club cluster of more than 500, most of whom are tai tais and their young dancing instructors.
Link in bio @straits_times

???? No matter where you are in the world, the word "lockdown" has likely affected you one way or another.
Lexicographers said they picked the word because it had become synonymous with the experience of populations across the world as governments look to curb the Covid-19 pandemic.
Collins registered more than a quarter of a million usages of "lockdown" during 2020, against only 4,000 the previous year.
Other words included in the longer list of 10 words of the year include "coronavirus", "social distancing", "self-isolate", "key worker" and "furlough".

Other words included in the longer list of 10 words of the year include "coronavirus", "social distancing", "self-isolate", "key worker" and "furlough".

French President Emmanuel Macron said the country would deploy thousands more soldiers to protect important sites such as places of worship and schools.
The attack comes while France is still reeling from the beheading earlier this month of a middle school teacher.
The attacker had said he wanted to punish the teacher for showing pupils cartoons of the Prophet Muhammad in a civics lesson.
Link in bio @straits_times
????: AFP, EPA-EFE
#franceattacks #StraitsTimes

Gatherings outside homes could be increased from 5 to 8 people. Similarly, 8 visitors could be allowed on home visits, allowing larger families to congregate.
Link in bio @straits_times
üì∏: Lim Yaohui
#phase3 #coronavirus #covid19 #StraitsTimes

For almost 3 months, 102-year-old Madam Yap Lay Hong had not seen her son Alan Ho. But on Thursday, she was finally able to welcome him, and the durian he brought, with a big smile.
The centenarian who lives in Lee Ah Mooi Old Age Home is Singapore's oldest coronavirus survivor.
The reunion with her 73-year-old son was made possible after Singapore entered phase 2 of its reopening on June 19.
Link in bio @straits_times
üì∏: Alan Ho

The reunion with her 73-year-old son was made possible after Singapore entered phase 2 of its reopening on June 19.

Farewell to the ‚Äúgentle giant‚Äù.
Mourners gather to watch the horse-drawn carriage carrying the casket and body of Mr George Floyd on its way to a cemetery in Houston.
Mr Floyd, the African-American man whose death in police custody sparked worldwide protests against racism, died after being pinned down on the neck by a white police officer.
Family members and friends at his funeral delivered eulogies remembering him as a loving, larger than life personality while calling for justice after his death.
The policeman, Derek Chauvin, has been charged with second-degree murder and 3 others with aiding and abetting.
üì∏: Reuters, AFP, EPA-EFE
#GeorgeFloyd #StraitsTimes

comments: Guys please be reasonable. The government is quickly adapting approaches based on the situation! Things have changed alot in 6 weeks. They know masks helps, but 6 weeks ago, number of healthy people is higher, probability of spread is low, but irrational fear (selfishness, panic hoarding) was high so that was the recommended approach. But today, there's a higher spread in community over time, but higher trust in government to act (e.g. society observed how they quickly planning resources and manpower to create and give out hand sanitizers and now reusable masks), so the approach changed. It's about adapting quickly based on factors e.g. society, resources needed, time available, probability of virus spread. Not about staunchly sticking to 1 way just because you don't want people to criticise.

1. All events and gatherings with 250 or more participants to be suspended until June 30
2. Suspension of all social activities for seniors by government agencies will be extended for another 2 weeks until April 7
3. Operators of venues accessible to the public, such as restaurants and cinemas, are required to ensure separation of at least 1m between patrons
4. Employers strongly advised to allow their employees to work from home, or implement staggered working hours where telecommuting is not possible
Link in bio @straits_times
????: Ng Sor Luan
#coronavirus #covid19 #socialdistancing #StraitsTimes

Got photos or memories of what it means to be Singaporean? Your contribution could be featured in the National Museum of Singapore's exhibition, Home, Truly: Growing Up With Singapore, 1950s To The Present, presented in collaboration with The Straits Times. The exhibition will be held at the National Museum's Stamford Gallery from August 2020 to February 2021.
Home, Truly will explore moments and experiences in Singapore's history that express the identity and collective memory of Singaporeans. Featuring archival photographs, artefacts and digital interactives, the exhibition aims to encourage reflection and conversation on what it means to be Singaporean.

Submissions close on March 1. Selected responses stand to win prizes such as a Shangri-La staycation, photography masterclasses by The Straits Times and behind-the-scenes experiences in the ST newsroom.

Ms Rozanah Roza struggled with depression for more than 5 years as the mother of 3 children - 2 with severe disabilities.
In June 2012, days before her 25th birthday, scans revealed that the twins she was pregnant with had serious brain defects that were incurable.
Her marriage ended 2 years after they were born, leaving her, at age 27, a single mother of 3 children.
But even in the depths of depression, Ms Rozanah said she knew she had to pick herself up because her children depended on her.
Today, she is back on her feet, and wants to give back to society.
Link in bio @straits_times

Ms Rozanah Roza struggled with depression for more than 5 years as the mother of 3 children - 2 with severe disabilities.
In June 2012, days before her 25th birthday, scans revealed that the twins she was pregnant with had serious brain defects that were incurable.
Her marriage ended 2 years after they were born, leaving her, at age 27, a single mother of 3 children.
But even in the depths of depression, Ms Rozanah said she knew she had to pick herself up because her children depended on her.
Today, she is back on her feet, and wants to give back to society.
Link in bio @straits_times

In the meantime, Ms Chan will be going through a mastectomy, followed by reconstruction surgery and radiotherapy.

Two months after Ms Chan See Ting was diagnosed with breast cancer, Mr Ian Ng gave her his reply: "In this life you may fight more battles than most people, but from now on let's make them ours to fight together."
The couple have already applied for a BTO flat, are undergoing a marriage preparation course and plan to get married within the next two years.
In the meantime, Ms Chan will be going through a mastectomy, followed by reconstruction surgery and radiotherapy.
